statement:
What integral is defined by the following expression?

\begin{align*}\lim_{n\to\infty}\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{\pi}{4n} \tan\left(\frac{i\pi}{4n}\right)\end{align*}

(Do not evaluate the integral.)

sols:
We recognize that this has the form of a Riemann sum:

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{i=1}^{n} f(x_i) \Delta x\end{align*}

We identify

\begin{align*}\Delta x = \frac{b-a}{n} = \frac{\pi}{4n}\end{align*} and

\begin{align*}x_i = a + i \Delta x = a + \frac{i \pi}{4n}.\end{align*} This gives us that

\begin{align*}b-a = \frac{\pi}{4}\end{align*}

Now, notice that the function in question is $f(x) = \tan(x)$ and so

\begin{align*}
f(x_{i}) &= \tan(x_{i})\\
&= \tan\left(a +  \frac{i \pi}{4n} \right)\\
&= \tan\left( \frac{i \pi}{4n} \right)\end{align*}

and so we see that we can choose $a = 0$. This gives us that

\begin{align*}b = b-0 = b-a = \frac{\pi}{4}.\end{align*} Hence, the integral is

\begin{align*}\int_{0}^{\tfrac{\pi}{4}}\tan(x)\, dx\end{align*}

completing the question.
